\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The task of locating the global minimum of a continuous and differentiable
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:S\rightarrow R,S\subset R^{n}$
\end_inset

 is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{*}=\mbox{arg}\min_{x\in S}f(x)\label{eq:eq1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=\left[a_{1},b_{1}\right]\otimes\left[a_{2},b_{2}\right]\otimes\ldots\left[a_{n},b_{n}\right]
\]

\end_inset

Methods that aim to locate the global minimum finds application in economics
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "globalecon1,globalecon2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, physics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "global_physics1,global_physics2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, chemistry 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "global_chemistry1,global_chemistry2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, medicine 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "global_med1,global_med2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 etc.
 Also global optimization methods were used on some symmetry problems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "go_symmetry0,go_symmetry1,go_symmetry2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 as well as on inverse problems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "global_nonlinear1,global_nonlinear2,global_nonlinear3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In the relevant literature there are a number of global optimization techniques
, such as Adaptive Random Search methods 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "go_adaptive1,go_adaptive2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Controlled Random Search methods 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "go_crs1,go_crs2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Simulated Annealing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "go_sa1,go_sa2,go_sa3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Genetic algorithms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "go_ga1,go_ga2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Ant Colony Optimization 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "go_ant1,go_ant2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Particle Swarm Optimization 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "go_pso1,go_pso2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 etc.
 Moreover, many hybrid techniques have been proposed to tackle the global
 optimization problem such as methods that combine Particle Swarm Optimization
 and Genetic algorithms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "go_pso_genetic_hybrid1,go_pso_genetic_hybrid2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, methos that combine the Simplex method and Inductive search 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hybrid1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 etc.
 Because of the large demands that global optimization methods have on computing
 power, several techniques have been proposed that take advantage of modern
 parallel architectures 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gpu1,gpu2,gpu3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this work, an integrated computing environment is proposed for solving
 global optimization problems.
 In this the researcher can code the objective function in the C++ programming
 language and then formulate a strategy to solve the problem.
 In this strategy, the researcher can choose from a series of sampling methods,
 choose a global minimization method established in the relevant literature
 and possibly some local minimization method to improve the produced result.
 Similar software environments can be found such as the BARON software package
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "baron"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the MERLIN optimization software 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "merlin"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the DEoptim software 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "deoptim"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rest of this article is organized as follows: in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Software"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 the software is described in detail, in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Experiments"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 some experiments are conducted to show the effectiveness of the proposed
 software and finally in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Conclusions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 some conclusions and guidelines for future work are presented.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Software 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Software"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The software is entirely written in ANSI C++ using the freely avaible QT
 programming library, that can be downloaded from 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

https://qt.io
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
(Write some text more)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Installation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the present time, the software package can only be installed on computers
 with the Linux operating system, but in the future it will be able to be
 installed on other systems as well.
 The instructions to install the package on a computer are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Download and install the QT programming library from 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

https://qt.io 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Download the software from 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

https://github.com/itsoulos/OPTIMUS
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Set the 
\emph on
OPTIMUSPATH
\emph default
 environment variable pointing at the installation directory of OPTIMUS
 e.g.
 OPTIMUSPATH=/home/user/OPTIMUS/, where user is the user name in the Linux
 operating system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Set the 
\emph on
LD_LIBRAPY_PATH
\emph default
 to include the OPTIMUS/lib subdirectory e.g.
 LD_LIBRAPY_PATH=$LD_LIBRAPY_PATH:$OPTIMUSPATH/lib/:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Issue the command: cd $OPTIMUSPATH 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Execute the compilation script:
\emph on
 ./compile.sh 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Implemented global optimization methods 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The global optimization methods that have been included in the implemented
 software are presented below.
 In most of them, a local optimization method is applied at the end of the
 algorithm, in order to locate the global minimum with greater reliability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Differential Evolution.
 The differential evolution method is included in the software as suggested
 by Storn
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "de_main_paper"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and denoted as 
\series bold
de
\series default
.
 This global optimization technique has been widely used in areas such as
 community detection 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "de_symmetry1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, structure prediction of materials 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "de_symmetry3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, motor fault diagnosis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "de_symmetry6"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, automatic clustering techniques 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "de_symmetry7"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Improved Differential Evolution.
 The modified Differential Evolution method as suggested by Charilogis et
 al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gende"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is implemented and denoted as 
\series bold
gende
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Double precision genetic algorithm.
 A modified genetic algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doublepop_tsoulos"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is included in the software and it is denoted as 
\series bold
DoubleGenetic
\series default
.
 Genetic algorithms are typical representatives of evolutionary techniques
 with many applications such as scheduling problems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "genetic1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the vehicle routing problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "genetic2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, combinatorial optimization 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "genetic3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, architectural design etc 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "genetic4"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Integer precision genetic algorithm.
 The method denoted as 
\series bold
IntegerGenetic
\series default
 is a copy of the 
\series bold
DoubleGenetic
\series default
 method, but with the usage of integer values as chromosomes.
 This global optimization method is ideal for problems such as the TSP problem
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "tsp1,tsp2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, path planning 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "pathPlanning"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Grammatical Evolution applications 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ge"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Improved Controlled Random Search.
 An improved version of Controlled Random Search as suggested by Charilogis
 et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gcrs"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is implemented and it is denoted as 
\series bold
CCRS
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Particle Swarm Optimization.
 A PSO variant denoted as 
\series bold
Pso
\series default
 is also included in the software.
 The particle swarm optimization method was applied sucesfully in a vast
 area of problems such as parameter extraction of solar cells 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "psoApp1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, crystal structure prediction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "psoApp2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, molecular simulations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "psoApp3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Improved Particle Swarm Optimization.
 The improved Particle Swarm method as suggested by Charilogis and Tsoulos
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ipso"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The implemented method is denoted as 
\series bold
iPso
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Multistart.
 A simple method that initiates local searches from different initial points
 is also implemented in the software.
 Despite its simplicity, the multistart method has been applied on many
 problems such as the TSP problem
\series bold
 
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "multistart-tsp"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, the vehicle routing problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "multistart-vehicle"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, the facility location problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "multistart_fac"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the maximum clique problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "multistart_clique"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the maximum fire risk insured capital problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "multistart_fire"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, aerodynamic shape problems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "multistart-aero"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 etc
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Topographical Multi level single linkage.
 This method is proposed by Ali et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "tmlsl"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and it is denoted as 
\series bold
Tmlsl
\series default
 in the imlementation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The MinCenter method.
 In the software presented here, another multistart method has been included,
 which forms with the use of the K-Means clustering algorithm the regions
 of attraction for the the local minima of the objective problem.
 This method is denoted as 
\series bold
MinCenter
\series default
 and it was originally published by Charilogis and Tsoulos 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "mincenter"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Implemented local optimization methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proposed software uses in addition to global optimization methods and
 local optimization methods, which can be used in most global minimization
 techniques with the 
\begin_inset Formula $--$
\end_inset

localsearch_method parameter.
 The implemented local optimization methods are the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
bfgs
\series default
 method.
 The Broyden–Fletcher–Goldfarb–Shanno (BFGS) algorithm was implemented using
 a variant of Powell 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "powell"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
lbfgs
\series default
 method.
 The limited memory BFGS method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lbfgs"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is implemented as an approximation of the BFGS method using a limited amount
 of computer memory.
 This local search procedure is ideal for objective functions of higher
 dimensions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The Gradient descent method.
 This method is denoted as 
\series bold
gradient
\series default
 in the software and implements the Gradient Descent local optimization
 procedure.
 This local search procedure is used in various problems such as neural
 network training 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gradient1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, image registration 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gradient2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
adam
\series default
 method.
 The adam local optimizer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Adam"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is implemented also.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The Nelder Mead method.
 The Nelder - Mead simplex procedure for local optimization 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "nelderMead"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is also included in the software and it is denoted as 
\series bold
nelderMead
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Hill climbing.
 The hill climbing local search procedure denoted as 
\series bold
hill
\series default
 is also implemeted.
 The method has been used in various fields such as design of photovoltaic
 power systems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hill1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, load balancing in cloud computing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hill2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 etc.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Objective problem deployment 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Objective function coding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:A-typical-representation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows an objective function written with the functions required by this
 software.
 This code is used for the minimization of the Rastrigin function defined
 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}-\cos\left(18x_{1}\right)-\cos\left(18x_{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[-1,1]^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The functions shown in the figure have the following meaning:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
void
\series default
 init(QJsonObject data).
 The function init() is called before the objective function is executed
 and its purpose is to pass parameters from the execution environment to
 the objective function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
int
\series default
 getDimension().
 This function returns the dimension of the objective problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
void
\series default
    getmargins(vector<Interval> &x).
 The getmargins() functions returns in the vector x the bounds of the objective
 problem.
 The class Interval is a simple class that represents double precision intervals
 eg 
\begin_inset Formula $[2,4$
\end_inset

] is an interval with left bound the value 2 and right bound the value 4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
double
\series default
	funmin(vector<
\series bold
double
\series default
> &x).
 This function returns the objective problem 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 for a given point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
void
\series default
    granal(vector<
\series bold
double
\series default
> &x,vector<
\series bold
double
\series default
> &g).
 This functions stores in vector g the gradient 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla f(x)$
\end_inset

 for a given point x.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
QJsonObject    done(vector<
\series bold
double
\series default
> &x).
 This function is executed after the objective function optimization process
 is completed.
 The point x is the global minimum for the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

